<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="188" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d188">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/1433½</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to the
                                <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-22">
                                <hi rend="italic">22 March, 1918</hi>
                            </date>.</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I am much obliged to you
                        for sending these papers to me so promptly, but I do not find in them
                        sufficient cause for altering our position. They still do not answer the
                        question I have put to Lord Reading and to all others who argue in favour of
                        intervention by Japan, namely, What is it to effect and how will it be
                        efficacious in effecting it? The condition of Siberia furnishes no
                        answer.</p>
                    <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>W. W.</signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>